===Etymology===
From {{etyl|enm|en}} {{term|herte|lang=enm}}, from {{etyl|ang|en}} {{term|heorte||heart|lang=ang}}, from {{etyl|gem-pro|en}} {{term/t|gem-pro|*hertô||heart}}, from {{etyl|ine-pro|en}} {{term/t|ine-pro|*ḱḗr||heart}}. Germanic cognates: see {{term/t|gem-pro|*hertô}}. The Indo-European root is also the source of Latin {{term|cor|lang=la}}, ''cordis'', Greek {{term|sc=Grek|καρδιά|tr=kardiá|lang=el}}, Welsh {{term|craidd|lang=cy}}, Irish {{term|croí|lang=ga}}, Armenian {{term|սիրտ|tr=sirt|lang=hy}}, Russian {{term|сердце||tr=serdce|lang=ru}}, Lithuanian {{term|širdis|lang=lt}} and Albanian {{term|kërthizë||navel, central spot|lang=sq}}.

